**1890 - 1962** (72 y.o.) - British statistician, geneticist/biostatistician
- Eugenist, as [[Francis Galton|Francis Galton]] and [[Topics/Mathematics/People/Karl Pearson|Karl Pearson]]
- racist?…
- Richard Dawkins has called him “the greatest biologist since Darwin”
- teachings at [[Topics/Machine Learning/University College London|University College London]] (UCL) & [[Topics/IT-Computing/University of Cambridge|University of Cambridge]] (?)
- has <u>introduced</u>
	- the [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Statistics/p-value|p-value]]
	- [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Statistics/Hypothesis testing|hypothesis testing]] (null hypothesis, ...), …
	- [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Maximum likelihood estimation|Maximum likelihood estimation]] (MLE)
	- [[Topics/Mathematics/Statistics and probabilities/Statistics/Fisher's exact test|Fisher's exact test]] of independence
- <u>Books</u>
	- *Statistical Methods for Research Workers* (1925)
		- huge influence
		- modern experimental design
